{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f44c615b-95dd-4c50-b8c6-a2227e8a2eb7","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **Speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- If `dotnet tool install` isn't possible (read-only filesystem), use the **sidecar approach** or bake `dotnet-trace` into your image for production readiness.\n- For very high CPU where `dotnet-trace` is too slow to attach, fall back to Linux **`perf`** — but you'll need `SYS_ADMIN` / a privileged container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c3dc6681-f9bd-4fb7-acca-3444a5884389","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"5FC5:18DC54:28B305:30618D:69EAC63F"},"id":"66afb3e2-1389-48e6-aabf-8b8cebff90a6","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:24:24.708Z","parentId":"ea67ebbe-bcc5-4d7f-99f0-7165aa734188"}
